[5]
Date: Mon 21 Apr 2003
From: Susan Compton <susan.compton@yale.edu>

Survival of Coronaviruses in the environment
--------------------------------------------
ProMED-mail post "SARS - worldwide (60): cases 20030420.0972", quotes a CDC
expert as saying that the virus can remain potent on objects much longer
than previously thought: "....in their studies, they found that you could
still culture viable virus from surfaces after as much as 24 hours, which
is longer than we normally expect viruses to be able to survive in the
environment."
I am unaware of any literature on the environmental stability of human
coronaviruses, but rat coronavirus, which causes a pneumonia in rats, when
dried on plastic and then rehydrated 48 hours later is still viable. The
decrease in viral titer is 1000-fold after 24 hours and 10 000-fold after
48 hours (Laboratory Animal Science 43: 403-4).
--
Susan Compton
Research Scientist
Section of Comparative Medicine
Yale University School of Medicine
<susan.compton@yale.edu>
[The survival time of the SARS-associated coronavirus in the environment is
highly relevant to interpretation of the epidemiology of SARS. Like other
respiratory viruses with lipid envelopes coronaviruses are susceptible to
inactivation by heat, desiccation, lipid solvents, oxidising agents,
nonionic detergents, and ultraviolet irradiation. Some coronaviruses
exhibit unexpected (pH (3.0) stability. Survival times will depend on virus
genotype (for example, human coronavirus 229E is more thermolabile than
human coronavirus OC43), composition of the carrier and substrate (Susan
Compton has given an example for rat coronavirus), and specific
circumstances (for example, bovine coronavirus can remain infectious in
milk for many days). In general respiratory viruses transmitted in aerosols
or in droplets would be expected to have a limited range and duration of
infectivity, whereas viruses transmitted in a more protective medium, such
as feces, might be expected to contaminate the environment for longer
periods. The epidemiological situation in Hong Kong suggests that more than
one route of transmission is being observed in the case of the SARS virus.
- Mod.CP]
