Source: News briefs

[A] Taiwan (from Channel Asia News)
<http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/38009/1/.html>
Taiwan may have registered its first SARS death after an elderly man
suspected of suffering from the disease died over the weekend. The resident
of the offshore island of Kinmen died at Taipei's Veterans General
Hospital. Officials are investigating the case.
[B] India, Maharashtra (from ) 21 Apr 2003 20:16 IST
<http://www.rediff.com/news/2003/apr/21sars1.htm>
3 SARS cases in Maharashtra
---------------------------
Three members of a family have tested positive for SARS, according to
Maharashtra's minister for health, Digvijay Khanvilkar. [The 3], who came
to India 3 weeks ago, have been isolated in a ward of the Siddhartha
Hospital, he said. The family had visited Jakarta and [other parts of? -
Mod.JW] Indonesia recently. [One of them] was admitted to the hospital on
17 Apr 2003 and the other 2 on 19 Apr 2003. Their samples were sent to the
National Institute of Virology in Pune, and tested positive, Khanvilkar said.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[According to today's worldwide update from WHO [1][A] a cumulative total
of 3861 cases of SARS and 217 deaths (case fatality rate of 5.6 per cent)
have been reported through 21 Apr 2003. Since the last reported update, 495
new cases have been reported, reflecting to a large extent the additional
447 cases reported from China, which include "old cases" that had not been
reported (as discussed in [1][C] and in ProMED-mail posting SARS -
worldwide (60): cases 20030420.0972) as well as the new cases identified
since the last update on 19 Apr 2003. In addition, the United States has
now begun reporting only probable cases of SARS, so today's report from the
US reflects a decrease in the number of cases reported in the previous
update when suspected and probable cases were reported daily. As of 21 Apr
2003, 1873 SARS cases have been reported as having recovered, giving a
reported recovery rate of 48.5 per cent. As an aside, it would be helpful
to see an official Chinese analysis, either daily or weekly, by province to
help monitor the outbreak, rather than to rely upon newswires and speculation.
The newswire report from India [6][B] is a bit disturbing. As mentioned in
prior ProMED-mail postings, the current case definition for probable cases
of SARS is based on clinical and epidemiological criteria and NOT on
laboratory diagnostic testing, as the sensitivity and specificity of the
current diagnostic tests is unknown and under investigation. It appears
that the Indian cases had traveled to Indonesia, where local transmission
has not been documented as yet. The cases traveled 3 weeks before the onset
of this illness, whereas the current estimate of the incubation period for
SARS is 2 to 10 days. The newswire does not provide the clinical symptoms
of this supposed family cluster, but the epidemiological information
provided seems incompatible with SARS, unless there is local transmission
in Indonesia previously undetected, the incubation period can be as long as
3 weeks, or there is local transmission ongoing in India that has not been
detected as yet. We await further clarification of this, but are concerned
to read newswires now confirming cases based on laboratory diagnostic
testing. (This is not the first instance of this -- see ProMED-mail posting
SARS - worldwide (57): cases 20030418.0952). - Mod.MPP]
